		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Sooneeraz Monohur]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Tue, 04 Nov 2014 06:32:10 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=6247#comment-12489</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Dear Mr Clear,

I am from Mauritius and it&#039;s been a while that I have been reading your Monday and Thursday articles. The fact that I continue reading your articles means that I do agree with your views and appreciate your writing.

However, I could not share your views on the present article and I wanted to voice out my views to you as soon as I read the article. And then, I read the comments of others on the same article... most of them being from the european world and were very happy with your views, I thought it was a CULTURAL habit for you to keep a count on your leisure activities. What I mean is that for me, indulging in sport activities if it is not professional-wise, then it is a hobby, a past-time, something pleasureable, that I LOVE doing and there is no need to keep a count. I just like doing it, so I do it... the fact that I love doing it, progress will surely come and the day I stop doing it, it will be more because I am not interested rather than the other reasons that we usually come by. 

So, reading the comments posted theirein, I refrained from sending the above views of looking at sports as leisure and taking pleasure in doing it.

However, today, I read your article on FORGET ABOUT SETTING GOALS, and I must say, I am more agreeable to your views and I think this is where I can reconcile with you. Goal is important to make progress but systems are more important and even indispensable.

Leaving you with some food for thought... if you have not already done so.

Please keep writing... it is really appreciated.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Dear Mr Clear,</p>
<p>I am from Mauritius and it&#8217;s been a while that I have been reading your Monday and Thursday articles. The fact that I continue reading your articles means that I do agree with your views and appreciate your writing.</p>
<p>However, I could not share your views on the present article and I wanted to voice out my views to you as soon as I read the article. And then, I read the comments of others on the same article&#8230; most of them being from the european world and were very happy with your views, I thought it was a CULTURAL habit for you to keep a count on your leisure activities. What I mean is that for me, indulging in sport activities if it is not professional-wise, then it is a hobby, a past-time, something pleasureable, that I LOVE doing and there is no need to keep a count. I just like doing it, so I do it&#8230; the fact that I love doing it, progress will surely come and the day I stop doing it, it will be more because I am not interested rather than the other reasons that we usually come by. </p>
<p>So, reading the comments posted theirein, I refrained from sending the above views of looking at sports as leisure and taking pleasure in doing it.</p>
<p>However, today, I read your article on FORGET ABOUT SETTING GOALS, and I must say, I am more agreeable to your views and I think this is where I can reconcile with you. Goal is important to make progress but systems are more important and even indispensable.</p>
<p>Leaving you with some food for thought&#8230; if you have not already done so.</p>
<p>Please keep writing&#8230; it is really appreciated.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
